At the meeting of the Monitoring Committee of the Chamber of Deputies, you talked about a joint Czech-German project, whereby the laws of both countries of concerning public contracts were compared with each other.
What was it that specifically?
It is a parallel test, where we started about two years ago.
Simply put, it comes to the European legislature sets out how public contracts are to handle. Build on the national legislation. And finally, there is still the actual practical application.
We have compared all this, and although the review is not yet completed, we find very interesting differences. The laws in us are generally, maybe even more "strict and perfect", the actual application but is better in Germany in some of the parameters.
This confirms that it is not enough to establish new and more detailed rules. You must also deal with the actual application of the law.
To what extent can the project be you help? What emerges for you from this project?
Just such joint control could help that we cease to strive if apparently not especially positive effect to a perfecting of the law and the reduction and balancing of threshold values.
Economic efficiency means to purchase something at a reasonable price (which is not always the lowest price) and to exclude unlawful enrichment or even criminal acts.
But lowering thresholds for contracts not guaranteed that we will also achieve this goal.
Perhaps it is even so that we stress the system in this way only with excessive "paperwork", and those who are looking for loopholes in the system, have it much easier to exploit the system, as if the thresholds were higher.
